<DATELINE>MARYSVILLE, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The one millionth automobile produced by
Honda in the United States will roll off the assembly line Friday,
Honda officials announced Wednesday.
   The car, a Honda Civic four-door sedan, will be driven off the
assembly line by the first associate hired at Honda of America
Manufacturing in 1978, Al Kinzer. Honda refers to its employees as
associates.
   Honda said the production of its one millionth car in the United
States signifies rapid growth and customer acceptance of the
products made at the company's auto assembly plant in Marysville,
about 35 miles northwest of Columbus in central Ohio, and at its
engine plant in Anna in western Ohio.
   The car's engine, a 16-valve, four-cylinder fuel-injected
powerplant, was made at the engine plant.
   Kinzer was hired as manager of administration when Honda started
operations at Marysville in 1978. He now is plant manager of the
engine plant.
   Honda is the nation's fourth-largest car company in sales and
manufacturing. It began manufacturing in the United States in
September 1979 with production at its motorcycle plant in
Marysville.
   The auto plant at Marysville began production in November 1982.
The engine plant at Anna opened in July 1985.
   The company last month broke ground for a new assembly plant
near its Marysville operation. The new plant, called the East
Liberty Auto Plant, will make Civic four-door sedans.
   Honda, the first Japanese automaker to build cars in the United
States, employs about 5,900 people at its auto, motorcycle and
engine plants in Ohio, said Honda of America spokesman Roger F.
Lambert.
</TEXT>
