<DESCRIPT>  WINTER; HOLIDAY; CHARITY; TOY; VEHICLE; CLUB; PROFILE; UNUSUAL  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  ALMOST EVERYONE in the biker world has a nickname. It's just something that
happens out there riding in the wind.;   Heart Attack earned his name by
surviving 14 heart attacks.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  The Weekly  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  THIS SANTA HAULS TOYS ON A HARLEY  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     Doc earned his being a paramedic.;   Bear, who is part Cree Indian, was
known as Standing Bear while growing up in Colorado. In the biker world, the
name was shortened to Bear.;   Bear is explaining the world of motorcycling
enthusiasts who band together through their interest in American-made bikes.
They are united, too, by unspoken creeds of helping each other and using their
word as their bond.;   A 53-year-old man whose right hand is covered with
silver and turquoise rings, Bear stands tall in the doorway of his leather
shop in Niles. A steady stream of customers and biker friends stop to talk.;  
With his flowing grayish-white beard and long wavy hair, he bears a strong
resemblance to Santa Claus.;   This weekend, Bear, whose given name is Don
Schurr, will close his shop to make toy runs along with scores of other East
Bay bikers, including members of the Niles-based Black Sheep club, of which
Bear is a charter member.;   Saturday, Bear will strap his donation -- a
large, cuddly brown bear with a stocking cap and red ribbon around its neck --
to the back of his Harley-Davidson and ride to Sunol on the fifth annual toy
run to benefit the Viola Blythe Foundation. The run is sponsored by the
Travelers Club.;   Sunday, he'll be off on another toy run. Riding amid his
"brothers," as he refers to his fellow bikers, he will head to Sacramento and
drop a toy truck and car carrier set into the bins on the steps of the state
Capitol. The U.S. Marines will be there taking holiday donations for needy
families.;   Bear has made toy runs for as long as he can remember. He
promotes them in his shop, on a table filled with literature about
motorcycling organizations and benefit programs.;   The Black Sheep, which he
helped found 18 months ago, has been collecting holiday donations for the past
three months to contribute this Friday at a dance in East San Jose for
American Indian children, sponsored by the Sioux Warrior Association.;   The
image of bikers as a charitable group runs counter to the stereotype, Bear
says, but the attitude of helping others is as central to the biker culture as
the black leather jackets they wear.;   "There's always somebody to lend a
hand," says Bear, who worked 27 years for Southern Pacific, 10 as a commuter
train conductor. He's been in the leather business for 35 years, operating a
leather shop in Fremont for more than two decades years.;   "I've worked so
many places, been lied to or cheated. But that seldom happens in the biker
world. I don't worry about people stabbing me in the back. Your word is your
bond. You go back on your word and you're shunned. You mess up, you lose a
lot.";   Bear makes a point of distinguishing between those who ride
motorcycles for recreation and those "who live, breathe and eat motorcycles.";
  "We ride Harleys, not those rice-burners," says Bear, making a reference to
Japanese-made motorcycles. "Personally, I don't care what anyone rides as long
as he's a straight arrow.";   During this interview, Bear receives dozens of
phone calls.;   Strictly business calls are in the minority. Some callers need
messages relayed. He walks down the street with his portable phone, trying to
pass on a message to call home.;   Then Bear consoles a woman who is upset
because the alcoholic she's been trying help stay stober has fallen off the
wagon.;   Bear admits he's somewhat of a counselor in his culture, a position
he has earned by his ability to adapt through personal crises. One of the
toughest was losing his second wife and son in the same year to cancer, about
11 years ago.;   "I guess my wife and I just knew what we were dealing with,"
says Bear, who is the father of eight children and grandfather of three.;  
"We are both Christians. We joked, even at the hospice in Hayward, about how
she wanted two little girls and now she was deserting me.;   "She told me,
'I'll never leave you because you've got our daughters and as long as you're
taking care of them, you're taking care of me and you won't forget me' -- and
that's the way it's been," Bear says.;   The trust others place in him and his
judgment comes as much from his ability to take care of himself and keep
others in line.;   Last week, six intoxicated young adults on the street were
causing a ruckus. He heard the noise and got a glimpse of what was happening.
He moved to the doorway of his shop.;   As the group walked by, they taunted
him and circled around him: "Hey, old man, we're going to kick you so hard and
whip you. Get back inside before we hurt you, old man . . .";   Bear grabbed
one of the young men by the shirt collar, pulled him close to him and breathed
into his face.;   "Now you die," Bear told the young man, who became so
frightened that he wet his pants.;   "I'm 53 years old and 240 pounds and I
got this way by being able to take care of myself.";   The next day, the young
men were in his shop, apologizing, Bear says.;   Now they stop in frequently
at the leather shop where Bear goes about his business of selling people on
the idea of helping others.  </TEXT>
