<LEADPARA>  LARRY SEGHIERI is under siege from one of the world's biggest motorcycle
gangs.;   "They're trying to destroy me," the San Jose small-business owner
says.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Local  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  STANDING UP TO A WORD HOG  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     But there's more than business at stake. To appreciate this, you need some
background.;   About six years ago, Seghieri, then a 37-year-old sheet metal
worker, and some biker buddies were having a late-night discussion over some
beers.;   "I said something like: 'I'm tired of doing what I've been doing,' "
he recalled. "One of the guys suggested opening a motorcycle parts store. The
light bulb went off.;   "We started kicking around names. Way into the night,
someone came up with 'The Hog Farm.';   "Since we were all riding Harleys (as
in Harley-Davidson motorcycles) and since Harleys were pretty much known as
the classic 'Hogs,' it seemed right," he said.;   To appreciate the
significance of this revelation, you need a bit more background.;  
Milwaukee-based Harley-Davidson has been making motorcycles for 87 years. At
the end of World War II, when returning soldiers were buying them because they
were cheap, Harleys were likened to garbage scows -- fat, low to the ground,
exhaust belchers -- "Hogs.";   IT'S IMPORTANT to keep that historical tidbit
in mind because the Harley lawyers are building their case against Seghieri
around it.;   Anyway, Seghieri borrowed some money and leased a brick building
at Montgomery and West San Carlos streets near downtown San Jose.;   He
specialized in Harley parts. He hired reliable mechanics and put in a few
decor options -- chrome accessories, leather jackets, raunchy T-shirts, etc.; 
 Within a couple of years, "The Hog Farm" became San Jose's most popular
Harley parts store. Last year, it grossed about $1 million.;   By comparison,
Harley-Davidson had $600 million in bike and parts sales worldwide last year.
That's muscle.;   Now the giant bike builder is trying to muscle Seghieri out
of business because The Hog Farm is not one of 600 official Harley dealers.
The official Harley dealer, Golden State Harley-Davidson, is about 150 yards
down the road on West San Carlos Street.;   Harley-Davidson says Seghieri is
ripping off not only its good name but also the name "Hog," which, the
company's lawyers have pointed out in federal court, is a registered
Harley-Davidson trademark.;   "It's not that we have anything against Mr.
Seghieri; we just do not want the word 'Hog' or even 'H-A-W-G' to be used
negatively or to become generic, like aspirin," said Bill Wood,
Harley-Davidson's manager of trademark enforcement.;   HE TOOK great pains to
sound polite on the phone. But I got the picture.;   "I can't tell you how
many victories we've had or who they were," Wood said, "because most of those
people backed down and settled out of court.";   Sounds pretty intimidating.; 
 "They've got the money," said Seghieri. "They're trying to wear me down.";  
But he's got his own lawyers. And he said he'll fight.;   You've got to admire
him -- the little guy standing up to the self-righteous bully -- especially
when the cause is bigger than business.;   It's language.;   In Germany,
Harley-Davidson's biggest foreign market, it's the word "schwein." In France,
it's "cochon." In Italy, it's "porco." In Japan, it's "buta.";   "We do not
intend to go after foreign derivations, regardless of the markets," Wood said.
"We're only interested in the American word 'Hog.' ";   Somehow, that's not
reassuring. Harley-Davidson's claim on the word still sounds greedy. It ought
to be challenged.;   A little San Jose business could be the place to draw the
line.  </TEXT>
