<DESCRIPT>  VEHICLE; PROFILE  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  JOHN SPLITTGERBER just shakes his head in amazement as he looks out onto his
Harley-Davidson showroom, one of the oldest and largest in the country.;   
"I've sold more bikes the past two years than I have since I've been in
business," said Splittgerber, who's been peddling bikes in upstate New York
for around 50 years.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Drive  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  'HOG HEAVEN'
HARLEY, NEARLY BROKE A DECADE AGO, HAS ROARED
BACK TO PROFITABILITY BY IMPROVING QUALITY
AND MARKETING  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  See related article on this page  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     "I don't even have any used ones. I sold about 30 (used motorcycles) this
year. More than I ever have.";    Business for a number of other Harley
dealers also has been in high gear over the past few months.;   
Milwaukee-based Harley-Davidson Inc., the only U.S.-based motorcycle
manufacturer, says that current inventory levels are at an all-time low
because of accelerated demand. Meanwhile, much of the motorcycle industry is
fighting to escape a decade-long slump made even worse by the current
recession.;    Harley's 1990 profit rose nearly 15 percent to $37.8 million,
or $2.12 a share, from $33 million, or $1.91 a share, in 1989.;    Harley's
sales, including parts and accessories, totaled $864.6 million last year, up 9
percent from $790.9 million the previous year. Just a few years ago, the
company was on the brink of bankruptcy.;    Industry experts attribute its
turnaround largely to increased quality control, an expanded product line and
some innovative marketing techniques.;    But it has been a long road to
recovery.;    Before the Japanese invasion of the U.S. market in the 1960s,
Harley had very little competition. It became the lone American survivor when
Indian motorcycles ended production in 1953.;    But Honda Motor Co. Ltd.
stepped in and transformed the market almost overnight, selling lightweight,
colorful, easy-to-ride motorcycles that were hundreds of dollars cheaper than
a Harley.;    In 1959, 60,000 motorcycles were sold in the United States. By
the early 1960s, the Japanese giant was selling 60,000 all by itself, while
Harley sold 10,000 to 13,000.;    The market reached its all-time high in
1973, when the Arab oil embargo helped spur sales to 1.5 million. Harley went
along for the ride, even after it was purchased by AMF Inc. in 1969, selling
as many motorcycles as it could produce.;    In 1973, Harley held a 77 percent
share of the heavyweight portion of the market -- which includes those big,
distinctive motorcycles featured in such movies as "Easy Rider" and favored by
many law enforcement agencies.;    But the Japanese competitors had big ideas.
Their strategy: invade the lightweight market segment, go for high volume at
low prices, then move into the heavyweight division.;    Much of the Japanese
machinery was designed to look like Harley clones, although the quality was
higher.;    Under AMF, Harley expanded production at a fast pace -- from
27,000 motorcycles in 1969 to 60,000 in 1972 -- but product development was
ignored and quality plummeted.;    While only 5 percent of Japanese machines
failed to pass company inspection, as many as 60 percent of Harleys failed.
Because of missing parts, new Harleys often came off the assembly line
incomplete and simply sat in areas called "hospitals" until they were
finished.;    Sometimes, unsuspecting dealers did the dirty work.;    "We
fixed them. We made them run. It was rough," said Splittgerber, the
Schenectady dealer. 'We were not accustomed to that because the old company
made a good motorcycle. We had the bikes, but we couldn't sell them.";    By
1983, Harley's share of the heavyweights had plunged to 23 percent; Honda's
jumped to 44 percent.;    "There was a mess of bikes that AMF had built in the
factory in crates, stacked one on top of the other right to the ceiling,"
Splittgerber said. "They came to us and more or less begged us to take them.
They needed the cash. I said I'd take eight of them, and they almost kissed
me.";    Harley would not have survived without such loyal dealers.;   
Thirteen Harley managers bought the company from AMF in a leveraged buyout in
1981. There were numerous layoffs over the next few years, and the company was
forced to borrow heavily. There were even rumors of filing for bankruptcy.;   
"It was a terrible time to be working for Harley," said John Gaedke, a Harley
spokesman, whose father lost his job after 23 years with the company. "There
was one black Wednesday when they just came in and fired every engineer
without a degree," he recalled.;    The Japanese were indirectly responsible
for Harley's turnaround. The company learned tips from its foreign competitors
and improved quality and production while expanding its product line.;   
Harley also received help from the Reagan administration, which imposed stiff
tariffs against imported motorcycles from 1983 to 1987.;    In addition,
Harley introduced some innovative marketing techniques, like promoting test
rides. It fosters a familylike atmosphere through the Harley Owners Group,
which has more than 100,000 members nationwide and conducts club activities.; 
  Although motorcycle sales dropped precipitously during much of the 1980s --
from 1.3 million in 1984 to 505,000 in 1989 -- sales of larger bikes, like the
kind Harley makes, gradually rose. In 1984, larger bikes made up 12 percent of
sales; in 1989, it rose to 21 percent.;    Today Harley sells about 60,000
motorcycles annually -- starting at $6,000 for smaller bikes and at $10,000
for larger ones -- and holds about 60 percent of the market for larger bikes,
compared with Honda's 14 percent share.;    "We have about a 95 percent
loyalty ratio today," Gaedke said. "Once they buy, they stay, and I have yet
to see a Honda tattoo.;    "The idea is to get people into the family. That's
really what Harley is. It's not just a piece of hardware.";  The average;
Harley buyer; (box)96 percent are men, but the number of female buyers has
doubled from 2 to 4 percent in the last three years.; (box)Average age is
34.6.; (box)59 percent are educated beyond the high school level.; (box)56
percent are married.; (box)43 percent have children.; (box)Median household
income is about $40,000. (At Golden Gate Harley-Davidson in San Jose, owner
Rick Falzone said his customers have a median household income of around
$60,000.); Source: Harley-Davidson  </TEXT>
