<HEAD>Bikers Deliver Toys to L.A. Skid Row Mission</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 400 motorcyclists, from yuppie
weekenders in exotic leather to hard-core bikers in soiled denim
``colors,'' delivered toys to a Skid Row mission in a thundering
testament to good will.
   The walls of the Fred Jordan Mission echoed from the blast of
arriving and departing Harley-Davidsons, Hondas, Kawasakis and
other big road bikes as the members of the Harley Owners Group
(HOG) and other motorcycle clubs made their second annual delivery
for the mission.
   Some Skid Row residents looked astounded at the polished
machines, some of them festooned with Christmas garlands and
mounted by riders wearing red and fur-trimmed Santa Claus hats.
Others took the opportunity to collect empty aluminum soda cans
left by the riders.
   ``I think it's the neatest thing there is,'' said Ferdie
Chaddick of West Los Angeles.
   Resplendent in black leather pants and jacket, Chaddick watched
and laughed as Skid Row children and mission workers sat astride
his $16,000 Harley for a snapshot.
   It belied, he admitted, the old biker motto that nobody _
NOBODY, touches a man's machine.
   ``The thing with the mission run is, we just go along with
everything,'' said Chaddick, a Santa Monica glazier.
   The delivery to the Jordan Mission on Sunday was part of a
larger effort in which the Salvation Army said it expected 25,000
motorcyclists to drop off toys in the Dodger Stadium parking lot
for the Army's 1989 Toy Run.
   ``We enjoy it, and its great for these needy kids,'' said South
Bay Harley Owner Group member Skip Fottler, who made the run to the
mission with his wife, Mary.
   ``A lot of people think we're hellions, but we're trying to drag
down that old image,'' Fottler said. ``We have doctors, lawyers,
policemen, firemen. We're just a band of bikers.''
   The mission hopes to collect 40,000 new toys for its huge annual
Christmas party on Dec. 16. About 20,000 people are expected this
year, said Willie Jordan, widow of mission founder Fred Jordan.
   ``Last year, we expected 15,000, and we got 20,000,'' Mrs.
Jordan said. The mission ran out of toys and food bags, and about
3,000 people went away empty-handed.
   ``It was one of the saddest days in my life. I just wanted the
street to swallow me up,'' she said.
