<SECTION>  Drive  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  S.J. SHOP HAS EVERYTHING A HARLEY FAN COULD
WANT -- EXCEPT A SUPPLY OF BIKES  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  See related article this page  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     The side and back walls of this motorcycle shop, Golden State
Harley-Davidson in downtown San Jose, are reserved for parts. Everything a
bike rider would need to keep his or her Harley in working order is probably
available.;    Accessories and parts keep a steady stream of customers flowing
in and out of the West San Carlos Street shop.;    That's good news for owner
Rick Falzone because customers sure aren't coming in to see motorcycles.;   
Only one new motorcycle -- a '91 Harley-Davidson FXSTS Springer Softail
costing $13,652 -- and three used ones are on display.;    Business is good,
Falzone says. It's just that he can't keep inventory on hand. "When they ship
a bike, it's already sold," he said while pointing to a list of customers who
have put down deposits on yet-to-arrive bikes.;    Potential customers have to
browse through catalogs and other sales material to choose the model and color
of the bikes they want.;    Golden State Harley sells 150 new bikes a year and
75 used ones. "And I could easily sell 200 (new) bikes," Falzone said.;   
Getting enough merchandise from the Harley headquarters in Milwaukee is "a
problem," Falzone said. But the renewed popularity of the bikes, coupled with
their relative scarcity, keeps prices stable and high.;    Falzone opened
Golden State Harley in late 1986 and sold his first bike in January 1987.
Although he bought into the franchise when the parent company was in trouble,
Falzone said his business has grown steadily.;    He now has 14 full-time
employees, including a new mechanic hired last week, to try to cut down a
three- to four-week backup in the service department.;    Large shipments of
new helmets and boots also arrived last week as Falzone beat the usual fall
rush of pre-Christmas accessory orders. He estimates that 30 to 35 percent of
his revenue comes from the sale of parts and accessories.;    Falzone's
typical customer is a white-collar worker who rides on weekends as a hobby.
The perception of the Harley rider as a tattooed, black-leather-covered
motorcycle outlaw isn't accurate, Falzone said.;    Before opening his Harley
dealership, the 53-year-old Falzone worked in the computer industry. He's
single, a barber-shop-quartet singer and a weekend rider of a custom-built
bike.  </TEXT>
