<HL> In Beverly Hills, The Wildest Ones Aren't Hell's Angels --- Upscale Bikers Roar Around, But Their Pastel Machines Would Make Brando Cry </HL>
<AUTHOR> Kathleen A. Hughes (WSJ Staff) </AUTHOR>
<SO> </SO>
<DATELINE> LOS ANGELES  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It is almost midnight when more than a hundred motorcycles thunder into the ground level of the shopping-mall garage, right past the valet parking attendants, and pull to a halt. 

   Hell's Angels on a tear, no doubt. 
But wait. 
Some of these bikes are baby pink, lilac and mint green. 
The black leather jackets look too new, some of the riders too well-coiffed. 
Then Billy Idol, the rock star, dismounts from one of the Harley-Davidsons and with the rest of the crowd disappears into Durango, a nightclub. 

   Relax. 
Remember, this is on the edge of Beverly Hills. 
It is just another evening out for the local RUBs. 

   That stands for rich urban bikers. 
Baby boomers of the rebellious '60s now in cushy jobs, plus other affluent would-be Brandos, are tearing themselves away from their Easy Rider videos to join trendy new motorcycle clubs. 
Suddenly, vintage leather jackets that cost up to $3,500 are fashion statements. 
Harley-Davidsons, once the outlaw biker's wheels of choice, have become the latest Hollywood status symbol, leaving Porsches and Jaguars to the masses. 

   "It's the nouveau biker," announces Tod Breslau, executive director of Stock Exchange, a night club that is hosting a weekly biker night. 
"They wear leather and jeans, but they're kind of clean. 
You can smell the conditioner in their hair." 

   Motorcycles have become so essential that they are in the Neiman Marcus Christmas catalog. 
A red, white and blue Harley-Davidson with a white leather seat goes for $25,000 -- more than twice the price of a less patriotic, plain Harley. 
His-and-her black leather jackets with studs in the shape of an eagle are just $2,000 and $1,900 each. 

   "The next face you glimpse behind a motorcycle helmet could be a CEO's," says the catalog. 
Sure enough, there is 65-year-old William Kieschnick, former Atlantic Richfield Co. president and chief executive, posing with the bikes and clutching a red helmet. 
He and his wife are modeling the jackets, as are famous Los Angeles chef Wolfgang Puck and his wife. 

   No matter that the Kieschnicks aren't bikers, and are in the catalog only because they are "friends of the store." 
Or that Mr. Puck doesn't ride either because "it's very dangerous." (He has a point. 
A motorcycle rider is 10 times more likely to die in an accident than an automobile driver.) 

   There are plenty of real celebrity bikers, and they are giving the traditional hairy-chested Harley image a chichi slant. 
Harley-Davidson gave comedian Jay Leno a free bike for promotional purposes, but actors Mickey Rourke and Sylvester Stallone bought their own. 
The Bangles, a female rock group, and Michael Jackson are including Harleys in new rock videos. 
Two movie studios recently bought movie scripts about bikers. 

   Even Elizabeth Taylor has become a biker. 
Well almost. 
Earlier this year, Malcolm S. Forbes, Forbes magazine editor-in-chief, gave her a purple Harley to celebrate her new perfume line, "Elizabeth Taylor's Passion." 
But the usually chauffeured star lacks a driver's license, so Mr. Forbes drove the purple bike with Ms. Taylor and a purple teddy bear named Lizabear on the back. 

   Mr. Forbes, a motorcycle collector, is actually the high priest of respectability for motorcycling. 
With his own "gang" called the "Capitalist Tools," he has generated widespread favorable publicity for an activity that at one time belonged to the wild and reckless. 
"Bikes are like horses used to be to cowboys," Mr. Forbes preaches. 
"It's you and your horsepower. 
It's very personal." 

   The average RUB, if there is such a thing, tends to wax eloquent about camaraderie, Beverly Hills style. 
"If a Porsche breaks down on the side of the road, you don't see another Porsche pull over," explains Frederick Spiker, a pastry chef. 
"But if my bike breaks down, two Harleys pull over." 

   Then there is freedom and machismo. 
Some Beverly Hills bikers ride in groups of 50 or more, zooming through red lights on the way toward Rodeo Drive. 
No helmets for them, thank you, and no mufflers for their bikes. 

   Female bikers make riding a dating game on wheels. 
"It gives me a feeling of power and it's a great way to meet men," says Dianna Edwards, a 41-year-old sales representative who shows up at Durango in tight black leather pants and a red leather jacket. 
"Men think it's really hot." 

   That goes both ways, figures Kim Robinson, 33, who owns an indoor-plant design company. 
"With women in cars, you get a much better response on a Harley." 

   Gathering spots for RUBs are proliferating. 
On Sunday afternoons, more than a hundred upscale bikers, mostly professional people, may rendezvous in front of the Rock Store, a small grocery store in a canyon near Malibu. 
"I'm going through a divorce, and I wanted a way to channel my energy," says new Harley owner Albert Aragon, 32, an operations officer at First Interstate Bancorp. 

   One club, WW3, used to allow customers to drive their bikes up to the bar, until the fire marshal called a halt. 
Some women who wouldn't be seen within miles of traditional biker bars now routinely head for RUB clubs to meet nice, attractive fellows. 
At the Cathouse, women in black leather miniskirts, black lacy tops and spiked heels form a line that stretches around the block. 
"Guys on motorcycles are sexy," says Debbie Searcy, a young blond dental assistant wearing a black leather jacket. 
"They used to be hoods," she adds, "but now it's materialistic." 

   For sure. 
Beverly Hills bikers invest small fortunes in their look. 
Giuseppe Franco, a Beverly Hills hairdresser, paid about $10,000 for his Harley and put an additional $11,000 into a white paint job, chrome parts and other accouterments. 
"It's getting out of hand," concedes Mr. Franco. 
For too many, he says, the focus is getting to be, "Who has a better bike? 
Who has a bigger bike?" 

   Jeff Levy does. 
He is a clothing store owner whose Harley boasts a strip of green lizard skin near the speedometer to accent its special mint-green paint job. 
The additions cost $12,500; the bike was a mere $10,500. 
His leather jacket adorned with a painting of a sexy woman on a big playing card completes the look. 

   Women RUBs know how to make Harleys more fetching, too. 
Laurel Rosenberg, an actress who works at Beverly Hills Fur, painted her bike pink and plans to add fox trim to her boots and a mink tail to her key chain. 
A motorcycle, she says, "is something personal where you don't have to use your intellect. 
It's emotional." 

   So what do the Hell's Angels, the legendary bad boys of biking, think of all this? 
"It's not the wild and crazy days of the '50s and '60s," laments a hulking Angel who identifies himself only as "Dougster." 
He complains that "people in Hollywood are into the Harley-Davidson for the nightlife and glamour. 
They ride from their homes in Beverly Hills to the coast on weekends. 
Rarely do you see them on the highway touring across the U.S." 

   He and some other Hell's Angels are willing to mix in with Beverly Hills RUBs once in a while. 
But they still dress their Hogs in basic black. 

</TEXT>
</DOC>

