<HEAD>Bikers Help Pay Tribute to Jimmy Carter's Sister</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELLIOTT MINOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PLAINS, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sixty bikers guided their Harley-Davidson
motorcycles into a rural cemetery for the funeral of former
President Carter's sister, Gloria Carter Spann, an avid rider.
   Mrs. Spann, the last surviving sibling of Jimmy Carter, died
early Monday of the same cancer that killed three other members of
the family. She was 63.
   About 300 people, including Mrs. Spann's husband, Walter, and
the former president and his wife, Rosalynn, gathered at the
Lebanon Cemetery on Tuesday for a 30-minute graveside service.
   The mourners included men in business suits, women in Sunday
dresses and bikers in grimy faded jackets with club colors
emblazoned on the back.
   Walter Spann, his long hair tied in a pony tail, wore a black
leather jacket.
   Mrs. Spann belonged to the Georgia Motorcycle Rights
organization and was named Most Outstanding Female Motorcyclist in
the nation in 1978.
   The Harley-Davidson Motorcycle Co. sent a floral spray.
   Riding side-by-side on 30 motorcycles, the bikers led the
funeral procession from Americus to the cemetery, a few miles
southwest of Plains in rolling farm country. Eight bikers served as
pallbearers.
   John ``the Reverend'' Herlihy, a photographer and custom bike
builder from Melbourne, Fla., was introduced to the mourners by the
Rev. Jenny Jackson Adams, pastor of Morningside United Methodist
Church in Americus.
   The bearded middle-aged biker, with tattooed arms and long hair,
and wearing a black T-shirt emblazoned with ``Biker Lifestyle,''
stood at a microphone a few feet from the coffin. His voice cracked
with emotion as he remembered his discussions with Mrs. Spann.
   ``Please take some time and say a prayer for her because I know
she's in biker heaven,'' Herlihy said.
   The pastor described Mrs. Spann as a courageous person who lived
life to the fullest and was an inspiration for others.
   ``Gloria was tough and Gloria was wonderful,'' she said.
``Gloria was a private person and saw no real need to explain her
life to people. She did not seek the spotlight, but she was a light
_ bravest of the brave _ and of course she knew exactly what she
was up against with this disease.''
   Mrs. Spann had been diagnosed in December as having pancreatic
cancer, the same disease that killed her father, James Earl Carter;
her sister, Ruth Carter Stapleton; and her brother, Billy Carter.
   Adams said Mrs. Spann felt that Christianity can be meaningful
for all types of people.
   ``Perhaps it was part of her nature to transcend culture and to
transcend lifestyles in the way that she did and to bring out the
best in all kinds of people who thought of themselves as pretty
rough characters,'' Adams said.
</TEXT>
