<LEADPARA>  THE HOG Farm in San Jose features one of the most impressive inventories of
chrome accessories for overhead engines, sprocket covers and suspension
systems, as well as raunchy black T-shirts, in all of Santa Clara County.;   
But now, owner Larry Seghieri is begrudgingly considering stocking some new
merchandise in his popular motorcycle parts shop -- helmets -- which
California Gov. Pete Wilson made mandatory beginning next year.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Local  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  'ROAD DOGS' HATE HELMETS  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     "Maybe we can make it the hot item for Christmas," Seghieri sighed bleakly,
leaning against a glass display case full of chrome gas tank covers for
Harley-Davidsons, "Hogs," if you will, or more appropriately, the machines
that made American motorcycling famous or infamous, depending.;    The roar
from a Harley's 80-cubic-inch engine is like no other -- throaty, contentious,
untamable, threatening with one crank of the throttle to run amok.;    That's
what turns some people on and terrifies others. Not the machine; the wild and
wind-through-the-hair image exuded by the people who straddle them.;    "Are
they worried about safety, or just jacking us around?" asked Doug Bontempi, a
43-year-old air brush painter and self-described "road dog" who owns a 1990
Harley FXRs worth about $10,700.;    HE'S BEEN riding for nearly 25 years, 19
of them with the Hells Angels in Oakland and San Jose.;    "I remember being
in the car when I was a kid and seeing these guys come over the hill," he
said. "All that color, all that noise, hair blowing, everything.";    Bontempi
figures he's run more than 20,000 road miles a year over the years. And,
frankly, he looks it.;    He says he'll wear a helmet, because, "What else can
I do? It's a $100 fine every time.";    But I can't quite picture him and 200
other hog-straddling Angels roaring down Highway 1 in their crash helmets, and
I don't want to, either. I'd rather picture the scene whereby a lone
California Highway Patrol officer suddenly comes upon 200 leather-clad,
helmetless scofflaws and decides to beat it for an early coffee break.;    For
better or for worse, their affiliations and well-earned nasty reputations
aside, road dogs with the wind in their hair have been part of the California
scene, blacktop cowboys the rest of us have watched with fear, fascination and
a little bit of envy.;    If they want to risk their lives for the sake of
keeping up their crazy appearances, the government ought to let them. Laissez
faire: Let reckless road dogs die.;    I know you can't selectively apply the
laws.;    'BUT A lot of us have mellowed," Bontempi said. "We wouldn't still
be alive and on the road if we hadn't mellowed.";    There's a shred of
evidence to back him up.;    According to California Highway Patrol
statistics, 40 percent of the more than 500 accidental motorcycle deaths in
1989 involved riders between the ages of 15 and 24. Thirty-seven percent were
between 25 and 34.;    "Helmets aren't going to protect people who have no
business being on bikes," said Bill Shrum, 44, a marketing manager and Harley
rider. "The important thing is to make the test for the operator's license
harder. All you do now is run through some pylons at 10 mph in the parking lot
of the DMV.";    Other Hog Farm regulars wandered in. They weren't shopping
for parts. They were looking to vent their frustrations.;    Similar
frustrations are being vented in biker crossroads throughout California. But I
wonder if anyone has come up with a better slogan for a raunchy black T-shirt
than Larry Seghieri did.;    "A vote against Pete Wilson is a vote for
freedom!" When he announced it, the guys at the Hog Farm howled.;    I bet it
won't be the last howl the governor hears from the road dogs.  </TEXT>
