<HEAD>Malcolm Forbes Leads Motorcycle Rally For Muscular Dystrophy</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY15</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB McMAHON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEDMINSTER, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Malcolm Forbes, the 68-year-old leader
of the pack, hugged actress Elizabeth Taylor, pulled on a red vest
sporting a ``capitalist tool'' logo and climbed onto his Harley
motorcycle Sunday to ride for charity.
   The thunder of engines pierced the dewy morning air at Forbes'
estate as the millionaire publisher's motorcycle club kicked into
action.
   He then roared down the driveway, leading 45 bikes to a rally in
Elysburg, Pa., to help raise funds for muscular dystrophy research.
   The scene recurs on Sundays from spring through fall at Forbes'
estate, Timberfield. But on Sunday, Forbes, who appeared on Outlaw
Biker's magazine May cover, was riding for charity.
   ``We do this every Sunday but this is a worthy cause,'' said
Forbes, as he prepared to leave on his 2{-hour dash. ``We're sorry
Elizabeth can't come. She's going to chopper down.''
   Miss Taylor had planned to accompany Forbes but couldn't be his
motorcycle mama because of recurrent back problems.
   ``This is the first time I haven't gone'' on a Sunday outing
this year, Miss Taylor said.
   Forbes has been a motorcycling enthusiast for 20 years. He
introduced Miss Taylor to the sport last year. Last fall, Forbes
gave her a custom-painted purple motorcycle and the two exchanged
biker rings.
   Miss Taylor rode in Forbes' private helicopter to the rally at
the Knoebels Amusement Resort, where hundreds of other bikers were
expected.
   Before leaving his estate, Forbes presented a $5,000 check to
Willie Davidson of Harley-Davidson, which is raising money for
muscular dystrophy research.
   The event was sponsored by the Eastern Harley-Davidson Dealers
Association, said Forbes' publicist, Donald Garson.
   Forbes is the publisher of Forbes magazine, a business
publication that bills itself a ``capitalist tool.''
</TEXT>
