<HEAD>Honda of America Getting New President</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARYSVILLE, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president of Honda of America Mfg.
Inc. is leaving the position to become managing director of the
Tokyo-based Honda Motor Co.'s worldwide manufacturing operations.
   The new assignment in Tokyo becomes effective June 30.
   Shoichiro Irimajiri, 48, will be replaced by Hiroyuki Yoshino,
general manager of Honda's Suzuka factory in Japan.
   ``I look forward to this new assignment because it represents an
opportunity to guide Honda's plan of establishing a worldwide
manufacturing network with a complementary international parts
sourcing network,'' Irimajiri said in a statement released by the
company Wednesday night.
   Irimajiri will be responsible for both planning and operations
for all Honda manufacturing worldwide, including auto, motorcycle
and power equipment, as well as quality control.
   Irimajiri joined Honda of America as president in May 1984.
Before that, he was general manager of the Suzuka factory and
executive vice president of Honda research and development at
Asaka, Japan.
   In 1982, at the age of 42, he was appointed a managing director
of Honda Motor Co. Ltd., the youngest ever.
   Yoshino, 48, joined Honda in 1963. He spent most of his career
in Honda research and development and was executive vice president
of R&amp;D at Asaka. He also had primary responsibilities for both
Honda's international purchasing and data processing divisions.
   Honda, the first Japanese automaker to build cars in the United
States, began its operations here in September 1979 with production
at its motorcycle plant in Marysville, about 35 miles northwest of
Columbus. The motorcycle plant now employs about 320 people.
   The auto plant at Marysville, which began production in November
1982, employs about 3,700 people. The engine plant at Anna in
western Ohio began production in July 1985.
 
