<DATELINE> DETROIT  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Honda Motor Co. may soon set another first among domestic Japanese auto makers -- as a major exporter of cars it makes in the U.S. to markets abroad. 

   Honda has scheduled a news conference today in Columbus, Ohio. 
As previously reported, the company is expected to announce its decision to build a second assembly plant in Ohio. 
But sources familiar with Honda's plans said it also will unveil -- most likely at the news conference -- a more important long-range strategy to build cars in the U.S. and export them. 

   The company wouldn't comment on its plans but has been touting today's event as probably the most important announcement it has made to date in North America. 
Honda's top executive, President Tadashi Kume, will be representing the company. 

   Clearly, any decision to begin exporting cars from the U.S. would be a major step for Honda, with potentially significant political and economic rewards. 
Honda, the first Japanese auto maker to build a car in the U.S., also would join Ford Motor Co. and Chrysler Corp., both of which just announced new efforts to sell selected North American-built vehicles to Western European consumers, a likely target for Honda as well. 

   However, details of the program, including which markets might be targeted, couldn't be learned. 

   Aware of growing protectionist sentiment in Congress, Honda has been broadening its manufacturing effort in the U.S. for years. 
Any further increase here, such as an export program, would improve its political position with those who argue that Japanese companies have been exporting products to this market at the expense of U.S. jobs. 

   The company has repeatedly said it wants to build cars in the markets it serves. 
Honda already sells more cars in the U.S. than it does in Japan. 

   If the Japanese yen remains strong against the U.S. dollar, Honda would also likely benefit economically from building its export vehicles in the U.S. Khaled Majeed, international auto analyst with Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc., estimates that it currently costs Honda about as much to build its cars in the U.S. as it does to build them in Japan and then pay the extra transportation and other export costs. 

   If Honda were to build vehicles in the U.S. and then ship them for sale in Europe, the company could also benefit if the dollar remained weak against European currencies. 
That makes U.S. exports to Europe less expensive to buyers. 
Any major export program, however, probably wouldn't be fully under way for a few years. 

   Honda could also win an additional advantage: Cars built in the U.S. may not fall under the import restrictions that some European countries have placed on Japanese cars. 
A spokeswoman for the Delegation of the European Community Commission said she wasn't immediately sure whether a case, similar to Honda's, would evade the restrictions. 

   But she added that the location of the last "economically justified" substantial operation on a product generally defines the official country of origin. 
Honda currently imports many parts into the U.S., where it assembles cars at its Marysville, Ohio, plant. 
Honda said that U.S. parts and labor currently account for a little more than 50% of the content of vehicles it builds here. 

   "I think (Honda) would be exempt (from the European import curbs) the way things stand," said Mr. Majeed. 
"I don't think there would be enough screaming out of Europe saying they were skirting the restrictions." 

   Honda already has some operations in Europe, chiefly building products such as motorcycles and lawn mowers. 
Its only car production program in Europe is a joint venture with Austin Rover Group in Great Britain, under which Austin Rover is building a jointly designed midsized car for both the Honda and Austin Rover nameplates. 

   A major U.S. car-export program wouldn't be the first time Honda has built products here and sold them abroad. 
The company currently makes motorcycles at its Marysville plant and exports them to 15 countries. 
It recently announced that it would start exporting its top-of-the-line Gold Wing motorcycles to Japan. 

   Also, Honda this year began exporting a small number of its Accord model cars from Marysville to Taiwan. 
The company expects only to sell between 1,000 and 2,000 of the cars to customers in Taiwan this year. 
Honda also builds its Civic model cars at Marysville, and sources have said that the expected second plant in Ohio would be able to build Accords, Civics and the company's Acura luxury cars. 
That expansion of capacity would clearly be part of any export program. 

   Nissan Motor Ltd., Mazda Motor Corp. and Toyota Motor Corp. are also currently building vehicles in the U.S., but none of those cars are sold overseas. 

</TEXT>
