<HEAD>First U.S.-Made Hondas Unloaded in Japan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first American-made Honda cars imported to
Japan arrived Friday and were welcomed with a party on the ship
that brought them.
   Makoto Tanaka, spokesman for Honda Motor Co., said about 350
people attended a one-hour reception aboard the auto carrier Green
Bay, including U.S. Embassy personnel and Japanese government
officials.
   The ship's cargo was 540 Honda Accord coupes and 100 motorcycles
from Honda's plant in Marysville, Ohio, he said.
   Tanaka quoted Koichiro Yoshizawa, vice president of Honda, as
saying the arrival of Honda cars produced in the United States was
``the first concrete step'' by Japan's third-largest automaker to
meet ``flexibly'' an increasing worldwide demand for vehicles.
   Honda has said it plans to bring 4,000 American-made Hondas to
Japan in 1988 and hopes for annual sales of 50,000 by 1991.
   Atsushi Kawashima of the Ministry of International Trade and
Industry said Honda's importation plan was ``a very good action.''
   ``As a result of the yen's appreciation, it is natural that
Japan's imports be increased ... and that things like that are
happening during a major trend of imports flowing into Japan'' more
rapidly, he said.
   The yen has doubled in value against the dollar in three years,
making dollar-denominated imports cheaper.
   Last year, vehicle sales in Japan rose 9.9 percent to a record
4.5 million. Honda sold about 365,000, far behind Toyota with 1.9
million and Nissan with 1 million.
   Imported Accord coupes will be sold in Japan for about 2.6
million yen ($20,800) beginning April 22, a Honda official said.
</TEXT>
