   DETROIT -- Just when Detroit seems to be giving up on
"made in America" as a marketing pitch for its cars, other
folks are picking up the red-white-and-blue banner.
   And those other folks are two of Japan's largest car
companies, Honda Motor Co. and Nissan Motor Corp. For the
first time, they're aggressively advertising some of their
cars as American-built.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Honda, for example, is using two-page magazine spreads to
tout its new Accord wagon as "The amazing new car from Ohio
that goes around corners, up hills and overseas." The ad
notes that Honda makes the Accord wagon in just one factory
-- Marysville, Ohio -- and that from there the car is
exported to Europe and Japan.
   Meanwhile Nissan is airing, in the Midwest only,
television commercials that show a Toyota Corolla, Honda
Civic, Ford Escort and Nissan Sentra driving around a track
in a fuel-economy contest. After the Corolla and Civic run
out of gas, an offscreen voice declares: "In fact, this
year's winner wasn't built in Japan. And it wasn't the Ford
Escort either." Instead, the winner is the "all-new,
American-built Nissan Sentra."
   These pitches represent a big switch in marketing tactics
for Nissan and Honda. In the mid-1980s they seemed to
soft-pedal the fact that some of their vehicles were made in
America. They didn't want buyers to worry that those cars and
trucks might be of lower quality than the ones imported from
Japan.
   And as Japanese companies took a record 28% of the U.S.
car market last year, Detroit moved to distance some of its
brands from the "domestic car" label.
   General Motors Corp.'s Saturn subsidiary, which is aimed
at attracting import buyers, carefully keeps the parent
company's name out of its advertising. And GM's Chevrolet
division created the Geo brand to highlight the fact that
some of its cars are made not by GM but by GM's Japanese
affiliates and partners.
   Still, "there is some tugging at the heart strings to
support American products," says Eric Conn, a senior
advertising manager at Honda. That's particularly true in
such Midwestern states as Ohio, Indiana and Michigan, which
have been among the toughest markets for the Japanese auto
makers to crack.
   During the 1980s Midwest sales didn't matter much to the
Japanese, because their car shipments to the U.S. were
restricted and they never had enough to go around. But now
seven Japanese auto makers build cars or trucks in the U.S.,
which means they have plenty of vehicles to sell. And while
Nissan and Honda started their campaigns before the Gulf war
began, experts say the recent rise in patriotic fervor makes
"buy American" seem like the right theme for the times.
   But there's a risk: A non-U.S. based company, particularly
one owned by the Japanese, might come across as trying to be
something it isn't. "You have to be cautious of the character
and style of the campaign," says Stephen A. Greyser,
professor of consumer marketing at Harvard Business School.
"Some consumers may see it as pandering to flag waving or
another effort at exploitation."
   Some Japanese auto makers agree and want no part of the
Honda and Nissan approach. Mazda Motor Corp. has no plans to
advertise that the Mazda 626 and MX-6 are built in Flat Rock,
Mich., says spokesman Thomas McDonald.
   "We don't hide the fact that they're made in America," Mr.
McDonald says. "But it's dangerous to make knee-jerk changes
in advertising. It's a very shallow effort."
   Mr. Greyser, however, says such marketing tactics, if
tastefully done, can be effective. A foreign-based
manufacturer, he explains, can market the "realities of the
company," such as where the product is built, the fact that
American jobs are created and other related items.
   That's the story Honda's U.S. sales and manufacturing arm
says it wants to tell. Honda views itself as different from
other Japanese auto makers because it was the first one to
build cars in America (back in 1982) and because more than
half of the cars it sells in the U.S. are made in America.
   "Japanese companies so often are visualized as one, as a
single unit," says the company's Mr. Conn. "We aren't one
mass group. We're very proud of our contributions to the U.S.
We've earned the right to be here." He says Honda had wanted
to get its message out sooner but has struggled for years to
find a way to say it.
   The Accord wagon provides a handy vehicle, so to speak,
because it's the first Honda engineered and designed in the
U.S. (though only partially so) as well as built in America.
"It is all part of our commitment," Honda's ad concludes, "to
building a self-reliant car company in the United States that
can compete with any auto maker. Anywhere." In a related
series of ads, Honda also boasts that it exports its
American-made motorcycles and lawn mowers to a variety of
overseas markets. Honda's advertising was created by Rubin
Postaer &amp; Associates of Los Angeles, its long-time agency.
   Nissan's made-in-America commercial, unlike Honda's
advertising, appears only in parts of the Midwest, mainly
Ohio and Michigan. Being American-made "isn't much of an
issue outside that region," says John Rinek, Nissan's
national advertising manager. The advertising was created by
Nissan's agency, Chiat/Day/Mojo of Los Angeles.
   While other Japanese companies aren't following Nissan and
Honda, at least one Midwest Isuzu dealership is. It's John
Rogin Buick &amp; Isuzu of Wayne, Mich., a blue-collar suburb of
Detroit. Once a customer refused to buy a Buick from the
dealership, says general sales manager Lou Ward, because of
the dual franchise with Isuzu.
   So for the past several months the dealership has stated
in its local newspaper advertising that Isuzu Motors Ltd. is
partially owned (34.2%) by GM. The advertising also notes
that the Isuzu Rodeo off-road vehicle is built in the U.S. --
at Isuzu's plant in Lafayette, Ind. "People who wouldn't
consider buying one because they thought it was an import
might consider buying one now," explains Mr. Ward. "It would
make a big difference if {Isuzu} advertised this in the
region."
   American Isuzu, the Japanese company's U.S. marketing arm,
says it doesn't plan such a campaign, though it applauds
Rogin's ingenuity. "The Midwest is a tough market," says
Richard Gillmore, director of marketing services at Isuzu.
"If I were in {Rogin's} shoes, I wouldn't hesitate to do the
same."
   ---
   Beach Demands $1 Million
                                                                                                       

   Bruce Beach, who resigned as managing director of Ogilvy &amp;
Mather's Chicago office last month, is demanding $1 million
in an arbitration proceeding against Ogilvy and parent WPP
Group.
   Ogilvy said last month that Mr. Beach was leaving for
personal reasons. But in his demand for arbitration, Mr.
Beach says WPP "considerably diminished" his autonomy and
control over the Chicago office. He claims he is due the $1
million under a severance agreement that guarantees him twice
his annual salary if his "responsibility, authority,
autonomy, title" or other benefits are reduced.
   Mr. Beach charges, among other things, that WPP
"instituted substantial adverse changes" by interfering with
profit-setting, hiring and firing, and by eliminating fringe
benefits like first class air travel. He claims that WPP's
chief executive, Martin Sorrell, interfered with his
authority by, for example, meeting with executives at client
NutraSweet without consulting him. WPP declined comment.
   ---
   New Yorker Picks Goodby
                                                                                                       

   The New Yorker magazine awarded its ad account to Goodby,
Berlin &amp; Silverstein, San Francisco, bringing to an end a
long relationship with executives who worked at the former
Lord Geller agency.
   The account had been handled from 1972 through 1988 by
Lord, Geller, Federico, Einstein. When several top Lord
Geller executives quit in 1988 to form their own agency,
Lord, Einstein, O'Neill &amp; Partners, the magazine followed,
becoming one of the new agency's first accounts. Lord
Einstein earlier this month was merged and renamed Lord,
Dentsu &amp; Partners. Lord Dentsu pitched the account, along
with three other well-regarded small agencies: Deutsch,
McCabe &amp; Co. and Omon.
   Steve Florio, the magazine's president and chief executive
officer, said he had put the account up for review because
key people on the account left when Lord Einstein was merged
into Lord Dentsu. He said he was impressed that Goodby
Berlin's principals "all read the New Yorker and understand
the culture of the magazine." The magazine, published by
Advance Publications, has spent as much as $3 million on
advertising in past years, but Mr. Florio said current
spending is in the $500,000 range.
   ---
   Ad Notes. . . .
                                                                                                       

   NEW ACCOUNTS: Carvel Corp., Yonkers, N.Y., pulled its $6
million ad account from Hal Riney &amp; Partners' New York office
and awarded it to TBWA Advertising. Industry executives said
personnel changes at the client and at Riney were factors in
the switch. Carvel, a unit of Investcorp, said only that it
reviewed the account because of a planned "repositioning" of
the business; it wouldn't elaborate.
                                                                                                       

   Brown &amp; Williamson Tobacco pulled its estimated $8 million
to $10 million Raleigh cigarette account from
Campbell-Mithun-Esty, New York, and awarded it to Geer,
DuBois, New York.
                                                                                                       

   EARNINGS: Omnicom Group, New York, said fourth-quarter net
income was virtually unchanged from a year earlier at $17.1
million, or 66 cents a share. Revenue for the quarter rose
11% to $323.8 million from $292.6 million. For the year, net
income rose 11% to $52 million, or $2.01 a share, from $46.8
million, or $1.81 a share, in 1989. Revenue for the year
increased 17% to $1.18 billion from $1.01 billion. Omnicom's
holdings include the BBDO, DDB Needham and Tracy-Locke
agencies.
                                                                                                       

   WHO'S NEWS: Philip J. Balshi was named executive vice
president and creative director of Lintas:New York, a unit of
Interpublic Group. . . . Jacqueline Silver, former executive
vice president, director of research, at Backer Spielvogel
Bates, opened her own research consulting company in New
York.
