<DESCRIPT>  CALIFORNIA; VEHICLE; SAFETY; EQUIPMENT; LAW; CONTROVERSY  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  With his shiny black Harley Davidson beneath him, leather-clad biker Baldy Lox
gave voice to the anger felt by thousands of motorcyclists over the impending
enforcement of California's mandatory helmet law.;   "This country just isn't
as free as people think it is," said Lox, of Van Nuys, explaining his
opposition to the law that orders him to wear a helmet as of Jan. 1.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  California News  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  MUCH-DEBATED BIKER-HELMET LAW TAKES EFFECT JAN. 1  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     "It's a matter of freedom of choice, and it should be my decision," he
said.;   But underscoring the volatility of the helmet debate, Mary Price of
Sacramento described a different kind of anger, stemming from the death of her
son -- who wasn't wearing a helmet -- as a result of a motorcycle accident.;  
"He exercised his freedom of choice not to wear that helmet. And after raising
him nearly 19 years, I had no son," Price said. "I decided to exercise my
freedom of choice and try to get a helmet law.";   Son died in collision;  
Her son, Jimmy Holquin, died in September 1985 when his motorcycle collided
with a car that turned in front of him. After the accident, Price lobbied hard
for passage of the mandatory helmet law that will take effect next month.;   A
lawsuit seeking to overturn the law has been filed in Orange County. But
barring an unexpected injunction, all motorcyclists and their passengers will
be required to strap on a helmet beginning Jan. 1.;   The helmet law will
apply to anyone who sits astride a motorcycle in California -- from the
Hollywood bikers dressed in leather, long hair flowing in the wind as they
ride on the throaty roar of a  low-slung Harley, to mom-and-pop duos wearing
matching jumpsuits as they cruise on the well-cushioned purr of a wide-body
touring cycle.;   Failure to obey the law can result in a fine of up to $100
for the first offense, $200 for the second offense and $250 for subsequent
offenses. Court fees will about double the penalties.;   Violation of the law
could also affect motorcyclists' insurance rates. Bill Madison, a spokesman
for the Department of Motor Vehicles, said the department will make a final
decision this month, but it is "leaning toward assessing a (violation) point
for anyone not wearing a helmet.";   Joins other states;   With enactment of
the law, California -- which had previously required helmets only for those 15
1/2 or younger -- joins the ranks of states that require all riders to wear
helmets.;   But while 23 other states already have similar helmet laws on the
books, the effect of the law will be greater in California, where roughly 20
percent of the nation's motorcycles are registered.;   To those who have long
ridden the state's roads with the wind in their hair, the new law threatens
what many considered a birthright.;   "Feel the wind, man, that's the whole
joy of it," said motorcyclist Gene Swinnie of suburban Lakewood. "They're
taking all the enjoyment out of it. And that's not fair.";   Two themes;  
Those who disagree with the helmet law primarily base their opposition on two
themes -- personal freedom of choice and challenges to the claimed safety
benefits of wearing helmets.;   "It's not a good law for a number of reasons,"
said Paul Lax, California director of ABATE -- American Brotherhood Aimed
Toward Education. "This law involves what I consider an unprecedented degree
of government interference with personal rights.;   "They're saying, 'Because
we don't think you have enough sense to do this, we're going to make you,' "
Lax said. "But if you accept that rationale, you have allowed that to override
individual rights.";   Don and Lucy Lawson of Glen Avon, near Riverside, wear
helmets at all times. An accident on a narrow highway to Lake Tahoe convinced
them their decision was correct.;   Still, Don Lawson disagrees with the law:
"I would not ride without a helmet, but I think we should have the choice.";  
Or, as biker Jesse Aguilar bluntly put it: "If somebody wants to go and
splatter their brains out there, it's their decision.";   Opponents of the
helmet law have some high-profile supporters. One is rock star Billy Idol, who
says he doesn't wear a helmet even after a February 1990 accident in which he
severely injured his right leg.;   Busey backs law;   Actor Gary Busey, who
suffered severe head injuries in a December 1988 crash, initially was against
a mandatory law. But now he supports it.;   To those who pushed for the law,
while the helmet law may take away each individual's right to choose, the
benefits to the whole of society outweigh any loss of personal freedom.;   "It
is the duty of the state to enact laws for common good," said Bob Terry, a
legislative aide to state Assemblyman Richard Floyd, D-Gardena, author of the
helmet law.;   "We enact laws that prevent you from skateboarding on the
freeway," Terry said. "They don't allow pedestrians on the freeway. And that
interferes with the right of the skateboarder, the pedestrian.;   "All of
these laws are for the common good," he said.  </TEXT>
